  "prompt": "Is there an online calculator that shows work?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several online calculators that show their work, depending on the type of calculation you need to perform. Here are a few categories and examples:\n\n**1. Basic Math & Algebra:**\n\n*   **Symbolab:** This is a very popular and versatile calculator. It handles a wide range of topics from basic arithmetic to calculus, algebra, trigonometry, and statistics. It shows the steps to solve equations, simplify expressions, and much more. (symbolab.com)\n*   **Mathway:** Similar to Symbolab, Mathway provides step-by-step solutions for various math problems, including algebra, calculus, trigonometry, statistics, and more. (mathway.com)\n*   **WolframAlpha:** This is more of a computational knowledge engine than a simple calculator. It can handle complex calculations and provides detailed explanations and insights into the results. While it doesn't *always* show every single step, it often gives enough information to understand the process. (wolframalpha.com)\n\n**2. Calculus:**\n\n*   **Symbolab (Calculus Section):**  Excellent for derivatives, integrals, limits, series, etc.\n*   **WolframAlpha (Calculus Section):** Can handle very advanced calculus problems.\n\n**3. Statistics:**\n\n*   **CalculatorSoup:** Offers a wide variety of statistical calculators that often show the formulas used and some intermediate steps. (calculatorsoup.com/calculators/statistics/)\n*   **StatCrunch (Requires a Subscription):** A powerful statistical software package that is web-based.  It provides detailed output and analyses.  Typically used in college courses.\n\n**4. Linear Algebra:**\n\n*   **Symbolab (Linear Algebra Section):** Handles matrix operations, solving systems of equations, finding eigenvalues/eigenvectors, and more.\n*   **MatrixCalc:**  A dedicated matrix calculator that shows the steps for various matrix operations. (matrixcalc.org)\n\n**5. Chemistry:**\n\n*   **Easycalculation Chemistry Calculators:** (easycalculation.com/chemistry/) Several calculators for stoichiometry, molar mass, conversions, etc. Some show the steps.\n\n**How to Find More Options:**\n\n*   **Be Specific in Your Search:** Instead of searching for \"online calculator that shows work,\" try searching for \"online [type of calculation] calculator with steps\" (e.g., \"online quadratic equation calculator with steps\").\n*   **Read Reviews:** Look for reviews of online calculators to see which ones are accurate and reliable.\n*   **Check for Step-by-Step Solutions:** When you're on a calculator website, look for features like \"Show Steps,\" \"Solution,\" or similar buttons that indicate it provides a detailed explanation.\n\n**Important Considerations When Using Online Calculators with Steps:**\n\n*   **Accuracy:**  Always double-check the results, especially if you're using the calculator for important calculations.\n*   **Understanding:**  Don't just copy the steps.  Try to understand the underlying concepts so you can solve similar problems on your own.  The calculator is a tool for learning, not a replacement for understanding.\n*   **Limitations:** Some calculators may not be able to handle all types of problems or may have limitations on the complexity of the input.\n*   **Ads/Subscription:**  Many free calculators rely on advertising. Some may offer more features or remove ads through a paid subscription.\n\nI recommend starting with Symbolab, Mathway, and WolframAlpha for general math and algebra needs.  For more specialized calculations, try searching for calculators specific to that topic.\n",
